From: Richard Rohlfing <richard@rohlfingphoto.com>
Cleveland elementary kids return to school

While masks covered anxious smiles, there were a few teardrops too.

“They are the future scientists, engineers, politicians, astronomers, and a host of other possibilities that will explore their world, solve complex problems and work towards leaving a better place for their own children,” said superintendent Brian Phillips in his August school newsletter editorial.

Phillips went on to say that, despite the trying times, hope for a bright outcome should be the real “new normal.”

“Besides preparing them with the tools to read well, do complex math problems or solve scientific inquiries, we should also be arming them with a sense of optimism for their future.”

post_text:
From: Richard Rohlfing <richard@rohlfingphoto.com>

Second grade boys use summer for practices, scrimmages

While there were no formal league games for the 2nd graders this summer, they got together to practice and scrimmage several times against the Cleveland 3rd grade team. The young Clippers also had a couple of scrimmages against Eagle Lake, also a practice team.

“It was fun for the boys to get together and play, and they made the best of it,” said Andy Smith, who, along with Scott Lassiter, Mark Giebel and Nate Fuller, mentored years’ team.

To build hitting and fielding skills during scrimmages, the pitching mound was staffed by a coach…with a player standing alongside. Each batter got pitches until he put the ball in play, and there were a few more than nine defenders in the field.

post_text:
From: Richard Rohlfing <richard@rohlfingphoto.com>

U12 girls finish season

With no U10 softball this summer, the U12 team ranged from players going into the eighth grade this fall all the way down to going into the third grade. After a road trip to Lake Crystal on August 4, their season ended two days later with a game against visiting Mankato.

Collecting hits for the Clippers at Lake Crystal, where—facing superior pitching—they were shutout decisively, were Jocelyn Kortuem and Maya Lassiter. The Clippers did post runs against Mankato, 19 of them, but the Peppers crossed the plate five more times for the victory. Hits for the Clippers came off the bats of Taylor Wolf and Anna Lamont.

Against visiting New Ulm on July 28, the Clippers fell 25-2. Kaitlyn Flowers had the only hit for Cleveland and scored one of the runs. Lassiter scored the other. Before that, Mankato beat the host Clippers 21-13. Flowers and her younger sister Natalie had hits in that game as did Lassiter.

post_text:
From:
Richard Rohlfing richard@rohlfingphoto.com

U12 girls face older competitors

Continuing to square off against much more experienced competition, the Cleveland U12 girls team, which includes players as young as to-be third graders, fell to host New Ulm 11-2 last Tuesday and to visiting Mankato last Thursday.

In New Ulm, the Clippers truck out on 14 at bats. Kaitlyn Flowers got the only hit. Taylor Wolf and Maya Lassiter both reached first on a free pass and scored. Wolf’s run came in the third on off-target pitches while Lassiter crossed the plate in the fifth on a Jocelyn Kortuem ground out.

“That was a tough team,” said head coach Scott Lassiter. “Most of those girls looked to be much older. Their pitchers were throwing balls as fast as the 14U teams I have seen. However, I thought our girls did great. I am very proud of our sportsmanship and bravery. They were hitting really hard at us, and our girls stopped some fast ones.”

On Tuesday, the Clipper U12 girls host New Ulm. On Thursday, they have a rematch against host Lake Crystal.

Childhood Vaccinations During the COVID-19 Pandemic

Le Sueur County Public Health
June 29 at 3:47 PM ·

As parents have kept their children home during the COVID-19 pandemic, some pediatric medical appointments have been missed. This means some children have not received recommended vaccinations to help protect them from dangerous diseases. Talk to your child’s doctor or clinic to make an appointment so your child can be up to date on their vaccines. Clinics are taking steps to make sure visits are safe.
For more information, visit health.mn.gov/immunize.

As the Minnesota Department of Education works closely with the Minnesota Department of Health to plan for the 2020-21 school year, we want to hear from families about their experience with the distance learning this spring.

This feedback is extremely valuable to us. This information will allow us to help families as they balance the responsibilities of work and family, while also supporting student learning.

The survey is available here in English, Hmong, Somali, and Spanish.

Please share this survey widely with your families and on social media. The survey will close on June 30, 2020.

Thank you!

Heather

Heather Mueller, Ed.D.
Deputy Commissioner

Cleveland Public School Driver’s Education - CoVid Safety Plan

The health and safety of our students and staff is of the utmost importance. It is imperative that students/instructors with signs of or exposure COVID-19 symptoms, per MDH/MDE, please stay home.

Students and parents must sign a waiver form for behind the wheel training. Mr. Harmeyer will be sending the waiver form via email soon.

Students and parents will fill out a health form. Here is the link.

One student and instructor at a time in the vehicle.

The steering wheel, blinkers, seat, and any other knobs must be sanitized before and after the drive.

Both the instructor and student must wear a mask at all times during the lesson.

Mr. Harmeyer will be contacting students and parents to set up behind the wheel instruction time. We hope to start Behind the Wheel Training on Saturday, June 13, 2020.

Any questions please contact Mr. Harmeyer.

Classroom Drivers Training will be scheduled in

Late July or Early August

Mr. Harmeyer will be contacting you

Learning Material Drop Off Reminder

Cleveland Public School will be collecting Chromebooks, HotSpots, Text Books, Library Books, and other learning materials. When delivering, please do not get out of your car and please wear a mask for your protection and ours.

Please follow directional signage at the front of the school (6th street), during the following times:

Date:

Tuesday, May 26th

9:00 a.m. - 12:00 p.m.

1:00 p.m. to 3:00 p.m..

Chromebooks and HotSpots Dropoff:

Please place Chromebooks, Chargers, and HotSpots in a plastic grocery bag.

We will be collecting and inspecting devices for damage.

Text Books, Library Books, and other Learning materials

Please put textbooks in individual bags per teacher, and write the teacher's name on the bag, keeping the bag open for immediate inventory.

Put ALL library books in one bag. Label the bag Library Books.

Inclement Weather Alternative Date

TBD

Sincerely,

Cleveland Public School Administration

post_text:
Everyone can work to reduce the spread of COVID-19

Cover your coughs and sneezes with your elbow or sleeve, or a tissue and then throw the tissue in the trash and wash your hands afterwards.

Washing your hands often with soap and water for 20 seconds, especially after going to the bathroom or before eating. If soap and water are not readily available, use an alcohol-based hand sanitizer that contains at least 60% alcohol.

Avoid touching your face – especially your eyes, nose and mouth – with unwashed hands.

Stay home if you have cold- or flu-like symptoms, for 10 days after your illness onset and three days after your fever resolves without fever reducing medicine (whichever is longer), and avoid close contact with people who are sick.

Cleveland Public School will be collecting Chromebooks, HotSpots, Text Books, Library Books, and other learning materials. When delivering, please do not get out of your car and please wear a mask for your protection and ours.

Please follow directional signage at the front of the school (6th street), during the following times:

Date:

Tuesday, May 26th

9:00 a.m. - 12:00 p.m.

1:00 p.m. to 3:00 p.m..

Chromebooks and HotSpots Dropoff:

Please place Chromebooks, Chargers, and HotSpots in a plastic grocery bag.

We will be collecting and inspecting devices for damage.

Text Books, Library Books, and other Learning materials

Please put textbooks in individual bags per teacher, please write the teacher's name on the bag and keep open for immediate inventory.

Put ALL library books in one bag. Label the bag Library Books.

Inclement Weather Alternative Date

TBD

Sincerely,

Cleveland Public School Administration

post_text: McKenna Robb, thank you for the kind message! We are grateful for the Class of 2020! We are doing our best to make the best of the situation that has been dealt to us all. Thank you and stay safe!
shared_text:
McKenna Robb‎Cleveland Clippers
May 1 at 6:01 PM ·

I would like to thank the staff at CHS for continuously going out of their way to support their students and especially the Class of 2020. The teachers, staff, and administration have been working so hard to make this transition easier for everyone. Throughout this difficult time, Principal Lusk and Mr. Cink have been checking in with the seniors on Google Meets to make sure that we are all doing okay and to keep us updated. Today, we picked up our caps and gowns and senior lunch from the school (all while social distancing). A special thank you to the lunch ladies for preparing such an awesome lunch for the seniors. While driving to the front of the school to pick up our caps and gowns, we were greeted by all of the teachers, staff, and administration. I think I can speak for the entire Class of 2020 by saying that we are so thankful and blessed to be a part of such an amazing school and community. It is so apparent how hard everyone is working to make this difficult time better for us all. I will forever be proud to be a Cleveland Clipper.

CAR PARADE INFORMATION

Cleveland Public School would like for all of our parents and students to be part of a car parade on Monday, May 4th from 6:00 p.m. - 7:00 p.m.

The Cleveland Public School staff will be standing on 6th Street waiting to see all of our students and parents.

Parents or students driving cars we would like you to follow these recommendations:

Please only have your own children in your car.

Please do not stop your car in the street.

Please do not get out of your car.

This will be a single lane “one-way” way parade, entering only from Broadway & 6th, and exiting only at 6th & Columbia.

Staff we would like you follow these recommendations:

Any staff who want to line up on 6th Street are invited to attend.

All staff attending will social distance on the sidewalk; a minimum of 6 feet apart.

All staff opting to attend are asked to wear a face mask.

Staff please do not park on 6th Street.

Staff will social distance and disperse the school area at 7:00 p.m.

Please let Mr. Scott Lusk, Mr. David Cink or Mrs. Kally Remiger know if you have any questions.

Infinite Campus Messenger - We've been working out some issues with our email/messaging system, so we apologize if you received a message earlier. Please disregard that message.

You should be receiving this message:

Cleveland Public School is gathering information to better understand the needs of our Distance Learning for students and parents. We are asking our parents to take a few minutes to answer questions about our Distance Learning Plan. Your feedback is important and will help us improve the plan quality. You will receive more than one email if you have more than one child enrolled in Cleveland Public School. Please complete a survey for each child, as they are grade specific. Thank you for taking a few minutes to assist us with this necessary information to help us ensure a good learning experience for you and your child.

There will also be a link to the survey on the Infinite Campus Messenger email.

If you have any questions please contact Scott Lusk:
lusk.scott@cleveland.k12.mn.us (507)484-1301

post_text:
Today was the first day of Distance Learning. I was impressed with all the pictures! For the first day we had a few glitches and that was expected. If you run into internet issues please call your teacher to let them know. This can happen to teachers as well. That is out of our control and we will work together to come up with a plan to get you caught up.If you run into any issues please call your teacher and let them know. We will be flexible with things that are out of our control. I was impressed with the participation and interaction for our first day. I was able to talk to some 4th graders on Google Meet. That made my day.

Thank you students, parents, and staff for working together to make Distance Learning happen in 10 days!

If you have any questions please contact me at lusk.scott@cleveland.k12.mn.us or 507-484-1301

If you have some picture you would like posted please email them to me.

Have a great night!

post_text:
School Age Care Update 3-27-20

School Age Care will be provided from 7:00 a.m. to 4:00 p.m. for all students that are enrolled in Cleveland Public Schools that are children of Tier I Essential Workers from March 30th until May 4th. We will do our best to accommodate the children of Tier II workers as staffing allows. If we do not have enough staffing to meet the demand for SAC, Tier I workers will have priority. Please note the following statement issued by the Minnesota Department of Health regarding the use of School Age Care: The care for children of these workers is intended for extreme circumstances in which no parent or guardian is available to care for a child due to employment as a critical worker. Once Distance Learning starts all students will need to bring all their materials for Distance Learning.We will provide a Chromebook if needed. Please be aware that the Minnesota Department of Education states that School Age Child Care is childcare only, not Distance Learning instruction.

shared_text:
Cleveland Fire Rescue
March 20 at 8:42 PM ·

We will be looking to help people that are elderly and have underlying health conditions procuring supplies that may be needed without them having to leave their homes at this time.

We are a volunteer department so if you have an emergency please dial 911. If you need assistance getting supplies and don’t want to leave your home because you’re high risk contact us through the following means, in this order please.

1) City hall Monday through Friday 8am-4pm ——507-931-6380
2) Through Facebook messenger
3) 507-484-1315
4) clvfirerescue@gmail.com

This is something we never have done before so please be patient with us as we will be figuring it out as we go, but we are here to serve the community in anyway we can.

post_text:
Meal Program Update

We are excited that many students are participating in the school sponsored meal plan program. This program is free for all Cleveland Public School students or Cleveland residents under the age of 18.

Please email Monica Manzey at manzey.monica@cleveland.k12.mn.us or call her at (507) 484-1342 to order your meals. Your order needs to be in by 12:00 the day before.

If you live in Cleveland, you will need to come to the school's main entrance and pick your meals up from 7:00 am to 8:00 am.

Otherwise the meals will be delivered to your cluster bus stop at your normal bus pick up time.

If the bus normally comes to your house the meal distribution route follows regular bus routes and we will deliver to your house.

This is a friendly reminder that we will be following the school calendar for School Age Care, our Meal Program, and Distance Learning. The school calendar is located on the Cleveland Public School webpage under the district tab.

Thank you Monica, Dee, Margo and Lisa for all your hard work feeding our students!

Due to staffing concerns, we are changing the hours of our School Age Care Program to 7am until 4pm. This change will be effective Monday, March 23, 2020. This meets the current state statute of providing an extended day. Also please note that SAC will not be open Friday, April 10 and other regularly scheduled school holidays. Please contact Jen Ryg at ryg.jennifer@cleveland.k12.mn.us or Dave Cink at cink.david@cleveland.k12.mn.us if you have questions.

Thank you Jen Ryg and Heidi Phillips for all you hard work! You are appreciated!

post_text:
The Cleveland School Age Care program will be open starting on Wednesday, March 18 to district enrolled students that have parents employed as emergency workers. Here are a few key items to remember about the School Age Care Program:

-SAC hours will be 6am to 6pm Monday -Friday.
-SAC will follow the regular school schedule.
-Student must be enrolled in the district.
-Parent must be employed as an emergency worker as outlined by MDE guidelines.
-Students will be provided breakfast and lunch free of charge. Lunch staff requests that
meals are ordered by no later than 12pm the day before.
-If requested, the district will provide transportation to and from the SAC program at the
regular times for bus routes before and after school.
-SAC Registration sheets will need to be completed if the student is not already enrolled
in the SAC program. This provides emergency contact information for the SAC staff.

Please contact Jen Ryg or David Cink if you have any questions.

post_text:
Hello,

This is Monica Manzey, Food Service Manager of Cleveland Public School. All Cleveland Public School students are eligible for a free breakfast and lunch during our school closure during this time of crisis. The breakfast and lunch will be packed in one bag and will be cold meals. Please order meals by contacting me at manzey.monica@cleveland.k12.mn.us or 507-484-1342 please order by 12:00 p.m. the prior day. Today will be an exception. Please order your meals by 2:00 p.m. If you have any dietary needs, please indicate that in your communication with me.

This is Nick Klaseus, my staff will be delivering these meals at approximately the same time as your scheduled bus cluster stop pick up time. If you are requesting meals to be delivered and do not have a cluster stop please contact me at klaseus.nick@cleveland.k12.mn.us or 507-931-5460. In the future, we are exploring different options of delivering curriculum or any other school related items. We will keep you posted as needs change.

We look forward to working closely with our school families in these trying times.

post_text: We are hosting a career day at GO! Therapy on Friday, March 13th from 1:00-2:30. We get request very often from students for "observation" hours. However, given privacy regulations enforced by Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA), it is difficult to meet those requests. Instead, GO! Therapy is inviting students to our facility to meet with our speech and occupational therapists. Students will get an opportunity to learn about speech and occupational therapy careers. Students will get to tour our facility and there will be time for questions and answers at the end. Anyone interested in these careers is welcome to attend!

post_text:
We wish the luck of the Irish to CHS senior Brooklynn Anderley as she competes in Le Center’s Miss Shamrock Contest.

In the talent portion of competition in the Le Center Legion on Saturday, Anderley played on her clarinet the expansive Irish Ballads “Oh Danny Boy” and “My Wild Irish Rose.” She concluded with the lively “Irish Washerwoman,” upping the tempo as she went along.

Also competing were Allison McCabe of St. Peter High School and Erin Schultz of Le Sueur-Henderson High School. The coronation is Friday in the Le Center Legion at 7:00 pm.

post_text:
Cleveland Public School - Student of the Quarter

The Student of the Quarter program is meant to promote success in and out of the classroom. For a student to be a well-respected citizen, they must be able to balance many different areas of life. They must exemplify outstanding characteristics both as a student and as a citizen of the school and community. The student must be able to handle many different aspects of student life while maintaining excellence in the classroom. This award promotes students who take pride in Cleveland Public School, in their community, and in themselves.

Student of the Quarter 12th Grade: Alexis Wondra
Alexis is a student who always works hard, but makes it look easy. She’s very self-motivated and driven to do her best every day. She consistently goes above and beyond what is required of her and asks appropriate questions when needed. Alexis can also be found helping other students when needed, without doing the work for them. She always keeps a positive attitude, even when she might not be having the best day. Alexis is a great asset to our school.

post_text: The Cleveland Clipper athletic community welcomes back Justin Kaus as a basketball referee. Kaus was diagnosed with a form of leukemia at the start of the 2018-19 season and underwent rounds of chemotherapy and a stem cell transplant last February. He returned to refereeing in early January of this year and was one of the officials for the Clippers’ game vs Sleepy Eye St. Mary’s at Bethany on Saturday. His second game of the night, he said he got a little tired running up and down the floor during a fast-paced game but was able to keep up. Wearing a Team Kaus shirt from a fundraiser for Kaus, which was held at the Kato Ballroom last May, is Clipper coach Dan Fredrickson.

post_text: Thank you Cleveland Fire and Rescue volunteers for all you do for our community! Please read this post to help them out as well as yourself in case of a fire.
shared_text:
Cleveland Fire Rescue
January 17 at 2:41 PM ·

We are getting on the #hydranthero bandwagon!!

With this snow fall we are going to be running a contest, pretty simple for rules.
1. Shovel the snow around your neighborhood hydrant at least 3 feet out from any connections.
2. Snap a selfie or a video of you doing the work.
3. Post it to the comments in this thread.

Prize will be selected at random and will receive a ride to school in a fire truck! (Must go to CHS and be able to get to the fire hall) they will also receive a $10 gift card to BP in town for a hot cup of coffee or some gas for the snowblower! Do not need to be a student to enter!

Entries must be submitted Monday 1-20-2020 by 11:59 pm to be eligible for the prize. Please like and share this post to get the word out, and feel free to clean out more than one hydrant!

EDIT: We understand that the weather hasn’t been very warm/nice but we have a warm up on the way and are extending the deadline 48 hours! Share the news and post your submissions!

Hello,

Cleveland Public School will be closed Friday, January 17th due to inclement weather.

A K-12 e-Learning Day is in effect.

Please check the Cleveland Public School homepage at https://www.cleveland.k12.mn.us/. The information is also under the “Students” pull down menu under e-Learning resources.

School Aged Care will also be closed on Friday, January 17th.

All school activities and athletics are also cancelled on January 17th.

There is also no school for students on Monday, January 20th as the teachers have a Professional Development Day.

Thank you,

Cleveland Public School Administration

post_text:
Come and support our Cleveland After Prom Party on Monday, January 27, from 5-9 p.m. at Buffalo Wild Wings in Mankato! Just bring in the attached flyer, or mention the fundraiser, to the wait staff and 15% of your total bill (not including tax, gratuity, alcohol or promotional discounts) will be given to our After Prom Party! It can be used for either dine in or take out!

The After Prom Party takes place after the Grand March and dance, for all of the prom attendees and any Cleveland Junior and Senior students who wish to attend. It's an all-night safe lock-in type of event for the students, which includes decorations in the small gym, activities/games, entertainment, food, gifts and prizes. Please help support this great event for our students!

post_text:
Cleveland Public School Baseball

On Saturday, January 11, 2020, the 18U Summer Baseball program is having a bingo fundraiser at the Cleveland Legion starting at 6pm. This is the first year that Cleveland has had an 18u team. We are beyond excited to get things rolling to bring an experience and lifetime of memories to our student athletes. All proceeds from this event will go towards purchasing equipment, tournament fees, and other expenses, such as umpire costs, league fees, and field rental. With that, we are looking for parent/player volunteers to help us with selling cards, helping with food and/or bringing a dessert, and clean-up. If anyone is able to help us out with this event, please contact Coach Rogers

Cleveland Public School is excited to announce we will be having two elementary Holiday Concerts with our High School Holiday Jazz Band.

The date of our Holiday Concert is Friday, December 20th. The starting times for these events are at 10:30 a.m. and 1:00 p.m.

Please be aware that parking will be limited as our construction project has taken away the back parking lot. You will be able to park in the front of the school on 6th Street and any surrounding city streets. You may also park at Our Savior's Lutheran Church. We are sorry for any inconvenience this may cause.

We look forward to seeing you at our Holiday Concerts!

post_text:
Mylie Dylla entered the 2019-2020 National Scholar Society Student Poetry Contest and her poem was selected to be published in the National Scholar Society's prestigious book titled Award-Winning Young Writers of America 2019-2020. Thank you Mrs. Yule for encouraging your students to be creative.

Imagine The World…
By: Mylie Dylla

Imagine The World…
Peaceful And Friendly
With no protests about the most ridiculous thoughts.
With no street fights roaming in cities.
With no more littering or pollution around the world.
With more self-esteem in people.
With more confidence.
With more motivation.
With more believing.
With more responsibility.
With more kindness.
With more understanding.
And Most Importantly...

Treat others the way you want to be treated!
